ANACT establishing a committee to study the implementation of a residential builder
registrationsystem.
BeitEnactedbytheSenateandHouseofRepresentativesinGeneralCourtconvened:
1 1 Findings and Statement of Purpose. The general court finds that the New Hampshire
2 residential home building industry is essential to New Hampshire’s economic vitality, workforce
3 development, and housing availability. The general court also finds that while the overwhelming
4 majority of New Hampshire builders operate with integrity and professionalism, isolated instances
5 of fraud and abuse, often from out of state, have caused harm to consumers and undermined
6 confidence in the industry. The general court recognizes that leaders within the New Hampshire
7 residential building community have expressed a commitment to strengthening accountability
8 measures and supporting reasonable mechanisms to promote transparency and consumer protection
9 withoutcreatingunnecessaryfinancialorregulatoryburdens.
10 2 Committee Established. There is established a committee to study the implementation of a
11 statewide registration system for residential builders and contractors. For the purposes of this act,
12 “residential builder” shall mean a person or business entity whose primary source of income is
13 derived from the construction, reconstruction, or substantial renovation of residential properties
14 consistingof4orfewerdwellingunitsinasinglebuilding.
15 3 MembershipandCompensation.
16 I. Themembersofthecommitteeshallbeasfollows:
17 (a) Twomembersofthesenate,appointedbythepresidentofthesenate.
18 (b) Three members of the house of representatives, appointed by the speaker of the
19 houseofrepresentatives.
20 II. Legislative members of the committee shall receive mileage at the legislative rate when
21 attendingtothedutiesofthecommittee.
22 4 Duties. Thecommitteeshall:
23 I. Examine the viability, process, and necessity of implementing a statewide registration for
24 residentialbuilders.
25 II. Assess whether a registration system would enhance consumer protection and address
26 instancesoffraud,misrepresentation,exploitation,andmiscommunication.
27 III. Evaluate the scope and structure of a registration system, including eligibility
28 requirements, renewal standards, complaint procedures, fee structures, oversight, and disciplinary
29 mechanisms.

